    "narrative_and_justification": "Al-Qaeda frames its violence as defensive jihad on behalf of Muslims worldwide. Its propaganda emphasizes themes of Western \\\"crusaders\\\" and Zionists waging war against Islam, the suffering of Muslims in conflict zones, and the religious duty to fight occupying or oppressing forces. Leaders like bin Laden issued fatwas describing attacks on Americans as justified retaliation for U.S. policies in the Middle East:contentReference[oaicite:16]{index=16}. This narrative of vengeful holy war is used to legitimize mass-casualty attacks and rally support.",
    "target_selection_logic": "Al-Qaeda primarily targets symbols of U.S. and allied nations' military, economic, and political power, as well as local governments seen as collaborators:contentReference[oaicite:17]{index=17}. Preferred targets have included embassies, airports and airliners, warships, hotels, and city centers to maximize impact and publicity:contentReference[oaicite:18]{index=18}. The group also endorses attacks on non-combatant Western civilians as legitimate, and it has targeted Shi'a Muslims and other groups it deems heretical. Target selection is driven by strategic value (forcing foreign retreat, damaging enemy economies) and ideological justification, aiming for high casualties and media attention."
