    "operations_tempo_and_patterning": "At its peak (1990s–2000s), Al-Qaeda central orchestrated large-scale attacks infrequently (e.g., the gap between 1998 embassy bombings and 2001 9/11) but with massive impact. Currently, Al-Qaeda’s central command operates covertly and rarely claims operations directly, while its affiliates maintain a steady tempo of insurgent attacks in their regions. For example, Al-Shabaab carries out near-weekly bombings and raids in Somalia, and Sahelian affiliates strike military and civilian targets in Mali, Burkina Faso, and Niger frequently. Attacks often surge during spring and summer \\\"fighting seasons\\\" in conflict zones. Globally, Al-Qaeda has encouraged lone-wolf attacks, leading to sporadic incidents inspired by its ideology. Overall, the pattern is decentralized: sustained low- to mid-intensity violence by affiliates, with the central leadership providing ideological direction and occasionally attempting spectacular international plots through its branches."
