    "audience_targeting": "Al-Qaeda tailors its propaganda to reach both global and local audiences. Internationally, it produces content in English (and other languages) to inspire Muslims in the West to either migrate for jihad or conduct lone-wolf attacks. Locally, affiliates produce materials in native languages (e.g., Somali, Urdu) to recruit fighters and justify their insurgencies. The group often targets youth and educated Muslims who may be sympathetic to anti-Western sentiment, as well as communities directly affected by conflict who might see Al-Qaeda as protectors or avengers.",
    "platform_policy_responses": "Tech companies and governments have aggressively moved to remove Al-Qaeda content online. YouTube, Facebook, and Twitter ban official Al-Qaeda accounts and take down videos of its leaders. For instance, issues of \\\"Inspire\\\" magazine and al-Sahab videos are routinely purged from mainstream platforms shortly after upload. These pressures have forced Al-Qaeda to rely on the Dark Web, closed forums, or constantly shifting Telegram channels. The increased surveillance and quick removal of extremist content have limited Al-Qaeda’s open propaganda reach, although dedicated followers still circulate materials in less-regulated corners of the internet."
