  "risk_assessment_and_mitigation": {
    "risk_summary": "Al-Qaeda remains a significant transnational threat, though its capacity for spectacular attacks has been degraded since its early 2000s peak:contentReference[oaicite:45]{index=45}:contentReference[oaicite:46]{index=46}. The risk is twofold: its resilient affiliates continue to destabilize regions through insurgency and terrorism, and its ideology still inspires lone actors globally. The likelihood of a 9/11-scale attack is lower due to counterterrorism pressure, but Al-Qaeda’s intent to target Western interests persists. The group exploits ungoverned spaces to regenerate, so the threat can rapidly escalate if pressure wanes.",
    "vulnerable_sectors": ["Civil aviation and transportation hubs (high symbolic value targets)", "Tourism and hospitality (hotels, resorts frequently attacked by AQ affiliates)", "Diplomatic facilities and government buildings (embassies, military bases)", "Urban mass gatherings (markets, malls) in countries where affiliates operate", "Energy infrastructure in conflict regions (oil facilities targeted by AQAP, etc.)"],
    "likely_future_trends": "Al-Qaeda is likely to prioritize gradual growth through its regional branches rather than immediate global attacks. We may see a continued focus on local conflicts (e.g., in Africa and South Asia) to build strength. The group will try to exploit any security vacuums (as seen in Afghanistan post-2021) for regeneration:contentReference[oaicite:47]{index=47}. Ideologically, it will attempt to compete with ISIS by portraying itself as a moderate jihadist alternative that still targets the West. We may also observe Al-Qaeda attempting more targeted assassinations and smaller-scale attacks on Western interests overseas, as completely striking the U.S. homeland has become harder. If a new safe haven emerges, however, plotting for external operations could accelerate.",
    "recommended_mitigation_measures": [
      "Enhance intelligence sharing between countries to track Al-Qaeda facilitators and disrupt plots early",
      "Support capacity-building in frontline states (training and equipping local forces in places like Somalia, Sahel, Yemen) to combat Al-Qaeda affiliates on the ground",
      "Sustain counter-finance efforts to choke off donations and illicit funding, including stricter regulation of hawalas and charities",
      "Invest in counter-radicalisation programs and strategic communications to counter Al-Qaeda’s ideology, especially in prisons and online",
      "Maintain agile counterterrorism strike capabilities (e.g., drones, special forces) to eliminate high-value targets when spotted, while minimizing civilian harm to avoid fueling the jihadist narrative"
